results.title: MAP compile loops 1 & 2
results.brief_description:
The Memory and Place (MAP) project captures stories, feelings and memories that we attach to places we know. This compile, in two parts, presents some of those stories and excerpts from the MAP Collection project:
MAP #1: Brunswick (Froggie’s gone), Northcote (Westbourne Grove), Cohuna (Tom Olsson’s Cohuna), Kensington (ReLocated - The Venny kids), Collingwood (North), Dunolly (The Posidon rush)
MAP #2: Carlton (Lygon Street), Ararat (Memories of Ararat c1930), Preston (Festival of kites), Burnley (Stack)

results.title: North
results.creator_credit: Christos Linou, Spiro Economopolous and Christos Tsiolkas
results.brief_description: Collingwood - ‘Hit the North. The north is where they put most of the wogs.’ Utilising excerpts from Christos Tsiolkas’ novel ‘Loaded’, ‘North’ is a lyrical and haunting work about space and place in Melbourne’s inner-city northern suburbs. This short work reveals a history of migrant alienation and regret submerged underneath the asphalt, mortar and concrete of the modern Australian city.

results.title: Festival of kites
results.brief_description: Sponsored by the City of Darebin, this short video documents the Festival of Kites, organized by the North Eastern Melbourne Chinese Association and by the Australian Kite Association. An all-day event held in parklands in Preston, this multicultural event includes performances by comedians, Indian dancers and a Chinese Choir.

results.title: This is my world
results.brief_description: Leanne is a virtual popstar. The artist dressed as the character Leanne (modeled on an anime character) sings a sorrowful pop song about her lonely world. The video is shot in the liminal no-place space of the Shopping Centre.

results.title: Pet shop
results.brief_description: A four screen looping animation work, Pet Shop pulls at the heart strings with its adorably cute 2D animated animals. Corompt’s work uses reductive and stylised modes of representation, exploring how we engage with these synthetic characters. The unquie relationship that exists between spectator and subject, inviting the spectator to partake in an unspoken agreement, where they may teeter on the boundary of the objectivity and empathy, simultaneously acknowledging its artifice, while at the same time participating in its pathos.
